# Async Rust Network Scanner

A concurrent TCP port scanner and banner grabber written in Rust using Tokio.

This project was built as a learning exercise to explore:

* Async Rust
* Tokio task scheduling
* CIDR parsing
* TCP networking
* Service fingerprinting
* Trait-based protocol probing
* Concurrent scanning architectures

---

# Features

* Concurrent host scanning
* Concurrent port scanning
* CIDR range parsing
* Single IP scanning
* Async TCP connections
* Service-specific probing
* Banner grabbing
* Command-line interface using Clap
* Protocol abstraction using traits

---

# Current Probe Support

| Protocol           | Support |
| ------------------ | ------- |
| HTTP               | YES     |
| Generic TCP Banner | YES     |

---

# Example Output

```text id="9mxu0g"
Ip: 192.168.1.10
Port: 80 Open
Banner: HTTP/1.1 200 OK

Ip: 192.168.1.15
Port: 22 Open
Banner: SSH-2.0-OpenSSH_9.3
```

---

# Installation

## Requirements

* Rust
* Cargo

Install Rust:

```bash id="uxn2m1"
curl https://sh.rustup.rs -sSf | sh
```

---

# Build

```bash id="kg1lq1"
cargo build --release
```

---

# Usage

## CLI Arguments

| Argument        | Description                     |
| --------------- | ------------------------------- |
| `-i`, `--ip`    | Target IP address or CIDR range |
| `-p`, `--ports` | Comma-separated list of ports   |

---

## Scan A Single Host

```bash id="e8qpxv"
cargo run -- \
    --ip 192.168.1.10 \
    --ports 22,80,443
```

Or using short flags:

```bash id="ww8n6h"
cargo run -- \
    -i 192.168.1.10 \
    -p 22,80,443
```

---

## Scan A CIDR Range

```bash id="rhh70p"
cargo run -- \
    -i 192.168.1.0/24 \
    -p 22,80,443
```

---

# Example

```bash id="uj5zrb"
cargo run -- \
    -i 10.0.0.0/24 \
    -p 21,22,25,53,80,110,139,443,445,8080
```

